				\begin{document}$$RS{A}_{t}={\mathrm{\alpha }}_{\mathrm{i}}+{\mathrm{b}}_{\mathrm{i}}\left({\mathrm{Time}}_{\mathrm{t}}\right)+{\upepsilon }_{i},$$\end{document}RSAt=αi+biTimet+ϵi,where αi is the subject-specific intercept that indicates the level of RSA at timet; bi is the subject-specific linear rate of change in RSA; and εI is a residual term that indicates the difference between the predicted value and the observed value of RSA. εI is distributed εI ~ N(0, σ2). The following three features were then extracted from each model for each patient: RSA intercept, RSA slope, and RSA residual standard error (RSE), which is the standardization of the variance of εI. Because the RSE is a measure of variability, it can be considered a measure of individual differences in RSA regulation where lower values reflected greater regulation of RSA throughout sessions. In the second step, these RSA features: 1) RSA Intercept; 2) RSA Slope; and 3) RSA Regulation, were entered together in linear regression models predicting PTSD symptom severity at post-treatment after adjusting for pre-treatment levels and modeled as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
